I thought about setting the nugget parameter before but didn't because I wasn't sure what value to set it to. Is there a way to come up with a reasonable nugget value when optimizing an unknown function?

For example, trying to optimize the following step function (maximum at x=7) produces the error after about 100 iterations:

```python
def step(x):
    if x <= 7:
        return int(x)
    else:
        return 14-int(x)

bo = BayesianOptimization(f=step, pbounds={"x": (1, 10)}, verbose=True)
bo.maximize(init_points=3, n_iter=1000, restarts=1)
```

Also the noisy step function:

```python
def noisy(x):
    return step(x) + np.random.randn()*0.25

bo = BayesianOptimization(f=noisy, pbounds={"x": (1, 10)}, verbose=True)
bo.maximize(init_points=3, n_iter=1000, restarts=1)
```

Setting the nugget parameter to 0.000001 makes it run for all 1000 iterations without an error - but I only guessed and I'm not sure if this might have any negative affect on the optimization.

